[Burying anthrax carcasses in quick lime was the traditional method of disposing of them. But then the light came on that adding calcium to the carcass might not be a good idea as the spores like high calcium levels. So bury them as deep as you can, making sure not to have done a necropsy. Otherwise the Kerala authorities have responded well, having disinfected the cattle shed, treated the other cows in the herd with streptomycin penicillin to stop any incubating infections, and they and the neighbouring herds are due to be vaccinated today (24 Jul 2015). That the vaccine had to come from the Veterinary Biological Institute at Palode tells one that the clinical veterinarians do not normally stock this vaccine, which indicates infrequent vaccination.

Anthrax is sporadic in Kerala. OIE records show bovine outbreaks in 2004, 2005 (1), 2006 (ProMED but not OIE), 2007 (ditto), and 2014 (2). Kerala is in SW India; see: http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/india_physio-2001.jpg. For Pathanamthitta, go to: http://www.fallingrain.com/world/IN/13/Pathanamthitta.html. - Mod.MHJ

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3534435,308.]
